{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"042444f7-3bcb-48f2-8379-3530f3f1d997","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## 1. File I/O During Evaluation (High Impact)\n**Line 13 in `.csproj`:**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nProperty functions that perform file I/O execute during evaluation, blocking the entire process. This is expensive and doesn't cache across re-evaluations.\n\n## 2. Recursive Wildcard Glob (High Impact)\n**Line 9:**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThe `**\\*.*` glob forces MSBuild to walk the entire directory tree during evaluation. This scales poorly as the repo grows and invalidates evaluation caches on any file change.\n\n## 3. Deeply Chained Imports (Low-Medium Impact)\n`EvalHeavy.csproj` → `level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props`\n\nThree levels deep isn't catastrophic, but chained imports add disk seeks and expand the evaluation graph. In larger repos this pattern compounds.\n\n---\n\n**Recommendations:**\n- Replace `ReadAllText` with a target that reads at build-time, not evaluation-time.\n- Narrow the wildcard to specific extensions/folders (e.g., `src\\**\\*.cs`).\n- Flatten or consolidate the import chain where possible.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"69772d13-449f-420b-87c6-c7be6999c16c","outputTokens":353,"requestId":"1C31:1A6B08:AB9B5E:C9061D:69F400E4"},"id":"3c82ab1b-4467-4a30-844d-6e49336842b3","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:25:00.917Z","parentId":"623c40f6-b263-4a64-8db5-f767e4112aa4"}
